<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="273" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1410,2045]" pageId="16" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1947,1973]" pageId="16" pageNumber="273">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name, an adjective, is derived from the Latin word “breviae” referring to the shorter terminal processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1323,2019,2045]" pageId="16" pageNumber="273" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1410,2045]" box="[199,1323,2019,2045]" pageId="16" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,2019,2045]" pageId="16" pageNumber="273">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[586,702,2019,2045]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Parabolocratus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lineatus">
<emphasis box="[586,702,2019,2045]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="273">T. lineatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter has subequal slender aedeagal processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
